      <comment>/* Historic counties of England */ wikilink an obscure term</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">A '''county town''' is the 'capital' of a [[county]] in the [[United Kingdom]] or [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].  County towns are usually the location of administrative or judicial functions, or established over time as the ''de facto'' main town of a county.  The concept of a county town eventually became detached from its original meaning of where the county administration is based (see [[County town#County Halls|County halls]] below). In fact, many county towns are no longer part of &quot;their&quot; administrative county e.g. [[Nottingham]] is administered by a unitary authority entirely separate from the rest of [[Nottinghamshire]]. Many county towns are in fact [[city status in the United Kingdom|cities]], but all are referred to as county towns irrespective of whether city status is held or not.


